YPUVJh4WHVM.title: Cafe Racer (Yamaha Bolt XV 950 by WalzWerk Motorcycles)
YPUVJh4WHVM.description:
(Legendado em Português)
Today's video, is about a very interesting Yamaha, which was developed to be an excellent platform for customization.
It is known by several different names like: Yamaha Bolt, Yamaha Star Bolt, Yamaha XV 950 Bolt, or Yamaha SCR950(Scrambler).
This video, explains how far you can go, to customize all these Yamaha models, showing one of the best Cafe Racers transformations I've seen, with the Yamaha bolt, and built under the Yamaha Yard Build program.
The custom Yamaha Bolt Cafe Racer presented on this video, was built in Germany, by WalzWerk Motorcycles. 
Marcus Walz is the founder of the company, and it is also the maestro behind the team who make people's dreams become a reality.
I am sure you will like it.

My special thanks to Pedro Torres, for his great help with my English.

nPqGvNYwyeM.title: Cafe Racer (Honda CB 750 "Seven Fifty" by Krisbiker Customs)
nPqGvNYwyeM.description:
(Legendado em Português)
Everyone knows, that the old Honda CB series from the 70's, is always an excellent choice for a Cafe 
Racer Project.
The big problem is, they are getting rarer, and too valuable.
And the solution to replace it, is usually the Honda 750 from the 90's.
The proportions may be very different compared with the CB series from the 70's, but it is doable.
This video, presents a very good example, of what can be done with that Honda "Seven Fifty".
But you can see also 2 other great projects based on the same Honda model, but with a more modern approach.
All these 3 projects, are the work of Krzysztof Rogalinski, also known by Khris, and the team of KhrisBiker Customs, in Poland.
I hope you like it.

My special thanks to Pedro Torres, for his great help with my English.

q-CEmz6mww8.title: Cafe Racer (Yamaha RD 350 by Bruno Hågensen)
q-CEmz6mww8.description:
(Legendado em Português)
If you are a Cafe Racer Purist, you are going to love this video.
Because this video is about one of the best, and well made 2 stroke machines I ever laid my eyes on.
Yamaha RD 350., a very popular motorcycle in the 70's, and still remembered as "the Widow Maker".
The beautiful Yamaha presented here, was built by Bruno Hågensen, from Norway.
And believe it or not, this motorcycle is not exactly the work of a professional.
But amazingly, the build quality is quite impressive.
I hope you like it.

My special thanks to Pedro Torres, for his great help with my English.

Here is a link to a 360 video about this Yamaha RD 350:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W89OJrJpUQA

The engine was totally rebuilt with the folowing modifications:
- A Lighter and stronger crankshaft. 
- Heavy duty clutch. 
- Electronic ignition. 
- High compression cylinder heads. 
- V-force 3 reeds. 
- A Pair of 34mm Lectron jetless self adjusting carburetors. 
- A Pair of JL exhausts with expansion Chambers in stainless Steel. 

Parts:
- Ceriani replica forks from 'CR' in Hungary
- Triple trees from 'CR' in Hungary
- Rear shocks from 'CR' in Hungary.
- Steering damper from 'CR' in Hungary.
- Custom made brake discs (320mm front and 220mm rear) from 'ISR' in Sweden.
- Levers with integrated switch gear from 'ISR' in Sweden.
- 2 brake calipers front and rear from 'ISR' in Sweden.
- Billet aluminium hubs front and rear, made for the Yamaha XS650, From 'Mike's XS' website.
- 'Motogadget' chronoclassic revcounter. 
- 'Motogadget' M-unit blue.
- 'Cognito moto' rearsets.
- Swingarm aluminium Alloy-SuperTuff made for the SR500 by 'MotoLanna Motorcycles' 

Custom made parts:
- Bracket for the revcounter. 
- Fork stem.
- Spacers for the wheels. 
- Baseplate for the seat made in 1mm stainless steel. 
- Cowl that goes all the way to the tank, made in a combination of fiberglass and stainless steel. 
- Caliper bracket front brake.
- Brackets that holds the rearsets, exhaust and rear brake pump, made by me in 10mm aluminium. 
- Bracket for the bottle you can see behind the engine, that's a bottle for 2-stroke oil, that I mix in the tank.
- Housing for the rear light.
